[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strait</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Strait
<hw>Strait</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Straits</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>straight</ets>, <ets>streit</ets>,
OF. <ets>estreit</ets>, <ets>estroit</ets>. See <er>Strait</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A narrow pass or
passage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He brought him through a darksome narrow <qex>strait</qex>⟦br⟧
To a broad gate all built of beaten gold.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Honor travels in a <qex>strait</qex> so narrow⟦br⟧
Where one but goes abreast.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Specifically: <fld>(Geog.)</fld> <def>A (comparatively)
narrow passageway connecting two large bodies of water; -- often in the
plural; <as>as, the <ex>strait</ex>, or <ex>straits</ex>, of Gibraltar;
the <ex>straits</ex> of Magellan; the <ex>strait</ex>, or
<ex>straits</ex>, of Mackinaw.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We steered directly through a large outlet which they call a
<qex>strait</qex>, though it be fifteen miles broad.</q> <rj><qau>De
Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A neck of land; an isthmus.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A dark <qex>strait</qex> of barren land.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: A condition of narrowness or restriction;
doubt; distress; difficulty; poverty; perplexity; -- sometimes in the
plural; <as>as, reduced to great <ex>straits</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For I am in a <qex>strait</qex> betwixt two.</q> <rj><qau>Phil. i.
23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let no man, who owns a Providence, grow desperate under any
calamity or <qex>strait</qex> whatsoever.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ulysses made use of the pretense of natural infirmity to conceal
the <qex>straits</qex> he was in at that time in his thoughts.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strait</ent>⟦br⟧

